switzerland.valueDescription: Switzerland has no de jure capital.

australia.valueDescription: Planned city built to overcome the rivalry between Melbourne and Sydney, which were both put forward as potential capitals for the nation in the Australasia Federation Conventions of the 1890s. Section 125 of the Constitution gives basic details about the location of the capital, size of the encompassing territory and so forth, while the Seat of Government Act 1908 specified its precise location.

equatorialguinea.valueDescription: Ciudad de la Paz is currently under construction and will become the new capital when complete.[6]

unitedkingdom.valueDescription: Prior to the Acts of Union in 1707, London was the capital of England only; Edinburgh was the capital of the Kingdom of Scotland. Sub-divisions of England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales

aruba.valueDescription: Self-governing country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.

newzealand.valueDescription: See also: Capital of New Zealand.

monaco.valueDescription: City-state. The Principality of Monaco does not have an official capital designated in its constitution, however, the Commune of Monaco, the country's only commune, is coterminous with the nation, making it the de facto capital.[7][8]

greenland.valueDescription: Self-governing country within the Kingdom of Denmark.

palau.valueDescription: Self-governing in free association with the United States. Koror was the capital of Palau until 2006.

sintmaarten.valueDescription: Self-governing country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.

ascensionisland.valueDescription: Part of the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha.

montserrat.valueDescription: British Overseas Territory. Plymouth was abandoned after the eruption of the Soufriere Hills volcano in 1997. Government offices since then have been moved to Brades, which is in the northwestern part of Montserrat.

marshallislands.valueDescription: Self-governing in free association with the United States.

curaçao.valueDescription: Self-governing country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.

taiwan.valueDescription: Officially the Republic of China (ROC), it has been competing for recognition with the People's Republic of China (PRC) as the sole Chinese government since 1949. Taiwan controls the island of Taiwan and its associated islands, Quemoy, Matsu, the Pratas, and part of the Spratly Islands.[Note 1] The territory of Taiwan is claimed in whole by the People's Republic of China.[Note 2] The Republic of China participates in the World Health Organization and a number of non-UN international organizations such as the World Trade Organization, International Olympic Committee and others under a variety of pseudonyms, most commonly Chinese Taipei.

peru.valueDescription: Cusco is declared as the \"Historical Capital\" (Spanish: Capital Historica), a merely symbolic statement, by Article 49 of the Peruvian Constitution.

india.valueDescription: Kolkata was the capital of India until 1911 during the British Raj.

somaliland.valueDescription: Unrecognized and self-declared state, de jure part of Somalia.

transnistria.valueDescription: De facto independent state, not recognized by any UN-member, but by Abkhazia and South Ossetia. Claimed in whole by the Republic of Moldova as the Territorial Unit of Transnistria.

nauru.valueDescription: Country does not have an official capital; however, the government offices are in Yaren.

micronesia.valueDescription: Self-governing in free association with the United States.

china.valueDescription: See also: Historical capitals of China. Sub-divisions of Hong Kong and Macau.

bolivia.valueDescription: La Paz is the highest administrative capital (3,650 m) in the world, higher than Quito.[5]

israel.valueDescription: The Jerusalem Law states that \"Jerusalem, complete and united, is the capital of Israel\" and the city serves as the seat of the Israeli government and its institutions. United Nations Security Council Resolution 478 declared the Jerusalem Law \"null and void\" and called on member states to withdraw their diplomatic missions from Jerusalem. Most countries currently maintain their embassies in and around Tel Aviv. The United States recognized Jerusalem as the capital and moved its embassy there in May 2018. [3] Many countries officially adhere to the proposal that Jerusalem have international status, as called for in the 1947 Partition Plan.[4] The State of Palestine, a de jure state, claims East Jerusalem as its capital. See Status of Jerusalem and Positions on Jerusalem.

srilanka.valueDescription: Until the 1980s, the capital was Colombo, where many important governmental institutions still remain and which is still designated as the commercial capital of Sri Lanka.

indonesia.valueDescription: A new purpose-built city named Nusantara in Kalimantan is planned to replace Jakarta as the national capital from the mid 2020s.[2]

faroeislands.valueDescription: Self-governing country within the Kingdom of Denmark.

nigeria.valueDescription: Lagos was the capital from 1914 to 1991.

sainthelena.valueDescription: Part of the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha.

cookislands.valueDescription: Self-governing in free association with New Zealand.

ivorycoast.value: Abidjan (former capital; still has many government offices)

pakistan.valueDescription: Karachi was selected as the first capital of Pakistan and served as such until the capital was shifted to Rawalpindi in 1958. Rawalpindi served as an interim capital for almost a decade until the construction in Islamabad was complete.

kosovo.valueDescription: De facto independent state that is recognised by 112 UN member states and by Taiwan. Claimed in whole by the Republic of Serbia as part of its Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija. Republic of Kosovo has de facto control over most of the territory, with limited control in North Kosovo.

yemen.valueDescription: Sana'a has been occupied by Houthis rebels since February 2015. Aden, the former capital of South Yemen, is Yemen's acting capital. See also: Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present).

burundi.valueDescription: Bujumbura was the capital from 1962 to 2018.

belgium.valueDescription: Also the de facto capital of the European Union.

tanzania.valueDescription: Dar es Salaam, the former capital and largest city continues to serve as the de facto seat of government hosting the presidency, government ministries, judiciary and diplomatic missions.

netherlands.valueDescription: The Dutch constitution refers to Amsterdam as the \"capital\". Also of the public bodies of: Bonaire, Saba and Sint Eustatius.

southossetia.valueDescription: De facto independent state recognised by Russia, Nicaragua, Nauru, Venezuela, Abkhazia and Transnistria. Claimed in whole by the Republic of Georgia as the Provisional Administrative Entity of South Ossetia.

niue.valueDescription: Self-governing in free association with New Zealand.

abkhazia.valueDescription: De facto independent state recognised by Russia, Nauru, Nicaragua, Venezuela, South Ossetia and Transnistria. Claimed in whole by Republic of Georgia as the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia.

kazakhstan.valueDescription: Formerly known as Astana; the name was changed on 20 March 2019.

egypt.valueDescription: A new capital is being built at the New Administrative Capital. It will reportedly be named Wedian.

republicofartsakh.valueDescription: The self-declared country remains diplomatically unrecognised by UN-member states, including Armenia. Transnistria, South Ossetia, and Abkhazia all recognise the state. Claimed in whole by Azerbaijan.

montenegro.value: Cetinje (Old Royal Capital, present seat of the President)

westernsahara.valueDescription: The Sahrawi Republic, recognised by 82 states, claims the mostly Moroccan controlled Western Sahara. Moroccan controlled territory includes El Aai\u00FAn, and Morocco claims all Sahrawi controlled territory. Tifariti is now the temporary capital (instead of Bir Lehlou earlier) of the SADR. Some government and military structures reside in exile in Tindouf, Algeria.[1] See Politics of the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic.
